USA: U.S. budget office says no "sequestration" needed.U.S. budget office says no "sequestration" needed.The Office of Management and Budget (OMB) said on Tuesday that it did not believe that any "sequestration" is currently needed based on U.S. budget law.Under U.S. law, across-the-board reductions in spending -- also known as sequestration -- enforce compliance with a series of constraints placed on the U.S. federal budget.These constraints include annual limits on discretionary spending.The OMB, in a document released at the White House, found that no such spending reductions are now necessary but added that it would issue a final report 15 days after the current Congress adjourns.